When venturing out to the borough of Brooklyn, you know that there is sure to be good food.  This was the case with Chela.  From the outside you would think this is a small restaurant but it runs deep with a full bar.  The seating can get a little tight during prime hours as this is a very popular spot among the locals.  When I walked in initially I was waiting for a bit for a seat as it was busy.  I got a table near the front entrance and that was fine.  All throughout my stay, the managers who were actively walking the floor, checked in on me every now and then even though there were periods of being crazy busy.  Cathy and Henry were very pleasant and courteous and were very helpful with suggestions as this was my first time dining at this establishment.  You get salsa and chips to whet your appetite while you wait for your food.  My server Jimmy was very polite, upbeat and super helpful. He knew about every dish that I had a question about and explained in very accurate detail the contents of each dish. He was very good at checking up on me and all the food came in a very timely manner.  Compliments to him and the diligent kitchen staff.  The dishes that I had decided on were:  *Tacos de Conchinita Yucutan style slow cooked pork, pickled red onions, sweet plantains queso fresco and cream.  There were three that came and they were all delicious!  *Tostada de Marisco The market fresh ceviche item included walnut puree, shrimp, calamari, octopus marinated in citrus juices.  It was spiced with habanero and Serrano with an array of vegetables that included sautéed onions, cherry tomatoes, cactus, cilantro and micro greens. This was one heck of an appetizer. The seafood was very fresh.  *Camarones Huatulco This awesome dish consisted of pan seared jumbo shrimp with mezcal chipotle emulsion, mango pico de Gallo and chunks of grilled pineapple (all beautifully plated and served on an actual pineapple).  This was one of the special menu items and it is very special.  *Nopales Salad Cactus was something I had seen only once before at another establishment in Manhattan.  So when I was able to get a small helping on the side I was ecstatic. The nopal is pickled and handmade so it has a bit of a sour taste that goes well with most savory entrees.  *Churros Vanilla bean with a special chocolate dipping sauce using 'abuelita chocolate' which is very popular in Mexico.  This is certainly a very casual busy place to bring friends but I had seen large parties walk in.  There is an area in the back to accommodate such groups. The noise level is quite high but that means that business is great...just like the food and service.

We will definitely go back!
